              "type": "lesson",
              "done": false,
              "content": {
                "title": "Introduction to Cash Handling",
                "type": "lesson",
                "media": {
                  "type": "none",
                  "url": ""
                },
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "id": "blk_001",
                    "type": "content",
                    "title": "Why Cash Handling Matters",
                    "body": "Proper cash handling is crucial for business accuracy and security. Even small mistakes can lead to significant losses over time. This course will teach you the fundamentals of handling cash transactions correctly and safely."
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "blk_002",
                    "type": "content",
                    "title": "Your Responsibilities",
                    "body": "As a cashier, you are responsible for accurately counting cash, verifying bills, making correct change, and securing the cash drawer. You must also be vigilant against counterfeit currency and theft."
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "blk_003",
                    "type": "content",
                    "title": "Basic Cash Handling Steps",
                    "body": "Always count cash twice - once when receiving it from the customer and once when giving change. Keep large bills separate until the transaction is complete. Never leave the cash drawer open or unattended."
                  }
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "title": "Counting Procedures",
              "type": "lesson",
              "done": false,
              "content": {
                "title": "Counting Procedures",
                "type": "lesson",
                "media": {
                  "type": "none",
                  "url": ""
                },
                "blocks": [
                  {
                    "id": "blk_004",
                    "type": "content",
                    "title": "How to Count Bills",
                    "body": "Start with the largest denomination and work your way down. Count each bill individually, placing it face-up in a stack. Organize bills by denomination before counting. Double-check your count before finalizing."
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "blk_005",
                    "type": "content",
                    "title": "Making Change",
                    "body": "Calculate change by counting up from the purchase amount to the amount tendered. For example, if the total is $7.35 and customer gives you $10, count: $7.35... $7.40 (nickel), $7.50 (dime), $8 (two quarters), $9, $10 (two ones)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
